GQDs were stable under all experimental conditions (Table 1
                        ) across the experimental period. The TEM images (Fig. 1
                        a, b) showed GQDs were monodispersed in DI water, and the average particle size of GQDs was about 5 nm.The GODs concentration kept constant (Fig. 1c) over a 3 h period. Meanwhile, the XDLVO energy barrier between GQDs particles (Fig. 1d) under all experimental conditions were higher than 10 mJ/m2, which is difficult to overcome to aggregate for GQDs. Although second minimum energy trap emerged with high ionic strength at100 mM, still the energy level was less than 0.005 mJ/m2, which could be easily overcome, suggesting the particles do not aggregate. Li et al. also demonstrated that GQDs exhibit excellent stability in monovalent cations solution [31].

The mobility of the GQDs in the experiment decreased with increasing solution ionic strength (Fig. 2
                        a). The recovery rate decreased almost one fourth from 93.84 % to 75.54 %, with the solution ionic strength increased from 1 mM to 100 mM (Table 1).The mobility of GQDs was significantly influenced by ionic strength of the solution as GO [35], although the mobility of the GQDs was much better than GO. It is due to the high solution ionic strength, and the repulsive interaction energies between GQDs and sand media is reduced. The zeta potential of the GQDs and the sand decreased significantly from -24.07 mV to -6.64 mV, when the ionic strength increased from 1 mM to 100 mM (Table 2
                        ). What’s more, when the ionic strength of the solution was as low as 1 mM, there was no secondary minima based on XDLVO theory. When the ionic strength increased to 100 mM, the secondary minima started to show up, about-0.00594 mJ/m2 (Fig. 2b). More GQDs could deposit on the surface of the sands due to the secondary energy minima.
